      {
        "id": 2323699,
        "name": "Ian Sutton",
        "username": "Ian_Sutton",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/ian_sutton/{size}/2266_2.png",
        "created_at": "2017-12-25T23:28:51.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Thanks Gerhard<br>\nThose wines listed I guess show our:<br>\na) modest outlay (in comparative terms - even cheap Pomerol carries a price). I guess we\u2019d be in the USD30-50 range in what we\u2019re looking for<br>\nb) General leaning away from the richer/blockbuster wines &amp; not afraid of lighter vintages/wines<br>\nc) Happy for Cabernet Franc to play its part in the blend</p>\n<p>FWIW that VCC was drunk a decade ago. and rather enjoyable it was then:<br>\n<em>Still healthy rich claret colour, though showing age at the rim.<br>\n<br>\nNot a particularly expressive nose, balanced between slightly fading fruit and cigar box, with a touch of orange. Some lovely aged character in there as well, but all these aromas are subtle.<br>\n<br>\nThe palate is medium bodied at most, with refreshing but balanced acidity. The fruit is a balance of subtle blackcurrant and orange, but as per the nose, is not striking. The tobacco element is very much in the mix as well. Lengthy finish and really nice balance.<br>\n<br>\nFar from a blockbuster, but awfully easy to drink and very flexible with food (we drank it initially alongside a game bird casserole - Pheasant / Partridge / Pigeon together with porcini &amp; slow pot-roasted in barbaresco)</em></p>\n<p>The two 95s felt like they needed more time, though what I wrote then suggested they might be better round about now.</p>\n<p>Intriguingly the 2009 La Croix du Gay didn\u2019t seem to be too OTT for us, though I was surprised it was so open. That suggests we\u2019re not completely against a slightly richer styled wine, though anything too plush/alcoholic is likely to disappoint (our experiences with St Emilion have often disappointed)</p>\n<p>Regards<br>\nIan</p>",
